{"/service/ndnp/fu/batch_fu_greenville_ver01/data/sn95047212/00529042334/1958032701/0062.xml":{"full_text":"Page 2\nlabor (Citizen\nA GENERAL NEWSPAPER\nDEVOTED TO THE BEST INTERESTS OF ORGANIZED LABOR\nPublished Every Thursday by\nThe LABOR PRESS, Inc. Charles F. Towle, President\nP. 0. Box 828 Phone PL 7-5031\nAdvertising Rates on Request\nSubscription Rate $2.00 Per Year\nEntered as second-class postal matter October 1, 1920, at the\nPost Office at Miami, Fla., under Act of Congress of March 3, 1879\nCHAS. F. TOWLE Editor\nJ. ED ISOM Advertising Director\nOfficial Organ of DADE COUNtFfEDERATION OF LABOR, MIAMI BUILD\nING TRADES COUNCIL, FLORIDA FEDERATION OF LABOR\nCITIZEN ADVISORY COMMITTEE\nEducational Committee of the Dade County Federation of Labor\n\u201cIFere it not for the labor press, the labor movement would not be what it is\ntoday, and any man who tries to injure a labor paper is a traitor to the cause.\u201d\n-SAMUEL GOMPERS.\nForum for Slander\nThe McClellan Committee\u2019s usefulness as an agency\nfor ferreting out improper activities in the field of labor\nmanagement relations can be permanently impaired by\nits investigation of the Auto Workers\u2019 strike against the\nviolently anti-union Kohler Co.\nThe hearings have deteriorated into a partisan political\nattack on the UAW by Senators Goldwater, Mundt and\nCurtis. They have created an atmosphere that could be\nprejudicial to the National Labor Relations Board\u2019s inde\npendent consideration of the evidence and the findings\nby a trial examiner that the Kohler Co. is guilty of unfair\nlabor practices.\nLast December, at the AFL-CIO convention, labor ex\npressed \u201cdeep concern\u201d that the McClellan committee\n\u201cmay allow itself to be used for political retaliation and as\na forum for the display of anti-union propaganda.\u201d\nThis concern has become a reality. Whatever con\ntributions the committee earlier made to exposing wrong\ndoing are being overshadowed by the current demonstra\ntion of hostility to the aims and objectives of unions to im\nprove the economic and social conditions of their members.\nThe AFL-CIO has made its position clear. It will con\ntinue to \u201ccooperate fully with all proper legislative com\nmittees seeking fairly and objectively to keep the labor\nmovement or any other segment of our society free from\nany and all corrupt influences.\u201d\nBut it will not respect a committee whose members\nabuse its processes to viciously slander the 'trade union\nmovement.\nRecession Danger Abroad\nAmerica\u2019s role as a leader of the free world is being\nseriously endangered by the worst U.S. recession since the\nend of World War 11.\nThe seriously weakened state of the American econ\nomy is impairing our ability to combat Soviet subversion\nand imperialism among the world\u2019s uncommitted nations.\nOur military strength, already weakened by the Ad\nministration budget policies, is further endangered by the\neconomy\u2019s downward slide.\nThe Communist world has been waiting since the end\nof World War II for a major U.S. depression as its best\nhope for achieving its goal of world domination without\nfiring a shot.\nThe plight of America\u2019s unemployed is serious\nenough. But coupled with a deteriorating condition in\nrelation to the struggle to maintain and strengthen the\nfree world, the current recession poses an acute danger.\nMacVicar-Wells, Inc.\nLUMBER and BUILDING SUPPLIES\n3445 N. Miami Ave. Miami, Fla. Phone Fit 3-4611\n*The Freshest, Cheeriest Flowers In Town\nSOUTH\u2019S LARGEST FLORIST J\nMiami Miami Beach Fort Lauderdale x\nI s\n/Qu refines ^^<>l\nI SUNSHINE FASHIONS*\n\n*reg. U. S. pat. off. v\n\nS Miami Miami Beach Ft. Lauderdale We\u00bbt Palm Beach C\nLABOR CITIZEN\nMarch 27, 1958\nResolution\n(Continued from Page 1)\ning our community agencies more\nrepresentative of the people and\nmore responsive to the people\u2019s\nneeds.\nTherefore be it resolved by this\nconvention of the Florida State\nFederated Labor Council, AFL\nCIO, that:\n1. There be established a stand\ning committee of our organization\non community services.\n2. This committee be assigned\na full-time director whose respon\nsibility it will be to carry the Com\nmunity Services program to all of\nthe unions in the state.\n3. We congratulate the national\nA F L-C I O Community Services\nCommittee and extend to it our\nappreciation of its past and pres\nent work and program.\n4. We strongly urge all local\nunions which have not already\ndone so to establish community\nservices committees both in be\nhalf of their own members and of\nthe communities in which they live\nand work.\nAn invitation for representa\ntives of the Federation of Labor\nto attend a dinner on Sunday,\nApril 6th at the Algiers Hotel,\ncelebrating the Third Sedar was\nextended by Histadrut. It was\nsuggested that President Owens,\nSecretary Votsch, Vice-President\nDrapkin and Treasurer Lazare\nwith their wives be authorized to\nattend.\nA meeting on Traffic Safety,\nsponsored by the National Safety\nCouncil will be held in Miami\nBeach on May 29th and 30th. A\nspecial invitation for President\nOwens to attend was accepted.\nPresident Owens, and Delegates\nDrapkin and Walton, members of\na committee appointed to call on\nStates Attorney Richard Gerstein,\nregarding the handling of com\nplaints of disgruntled union mem\nbers directed at union officials,\nresulted in some clarification of\nthe situation as regards future in\ncidents. Mr. Gerstein was in\nformed that certain disciplinary\nmeasures handled within the\nunions against unruly or recalci\ntrant members were handled in\ncompliance with the by-laws of\nthose organizations, and he agreed\nthat in such cases neither civil or\ncriminal action was applicable.\nThere was some discussion of\nthe necessity of finding a new\nmeeting place which would include\nan office for the Federation. Sev\neral places are being considered.\nAn offer by Community Services\nrepresentative Stephenson, for the\nuse of the meeting hall in the\nCommunity Services Building was\ntaken under advisement and will\nbe investigated further.\nOn motion from the floor,\nChairman Owens was authorized\nto appoint an alternate delegate\nto the Merger Convention at\nTampa, to take the place of Sam\nMacy, who is seriously ill in Jack\nson Memorial Hospital. President\nOwens appointed Eli Lazare.\nThere being no further business,\nthe usual motion for adjournment\nwas in order.\nA book that is \u201cgood\u201d is a book\nyou dislike to have come to an\nend.\nWe Don't\nPatronize...\nRed Adams Bus Line\nShell Super-Store, Inc.\nMiami Herald\nMiami Daily News\nHoward Johnson\nJune Dairy\nBonfire Restaurant\nGulfstream Press\nFlorida Sun\nSigned\nDADE COUNTY\nFEDERATION OF LABOR\nEaster Pageant\n(Continued from Page 1)\nBartholomew; and Glednig Knebs,\nPhilip.\nThe pageant is sponsored by the\nGreater Miami Ministerial Associ\nation and produced by the Drama\nDepartment of the Greater Miami\nCouncil of Churches. Serving on\nthe pageant committee are Dr.\nHarold Buell, pastor of White\nTemple Methodist Church; The\nRev. John Henderson, Riviera\nPresbyterian; The Rev. A. E. Gy\nsa n, Christ Lutheran; Leslie\nThompson, Minister of Music at\nRiverside Baptist.\nDr. William Wahl, Associate Di\nrector of the Council of Churches,\nis advisory director of the pageant.\nThe Rev. Luther A. Key, President\nof the Greater Miami Ministerial\nAssociation is also an ex-officio\nmember of the committee.\nErnie Seiler, Executive Vice\nPresident of the Orange Bowl\nCommittee is in charge of the sets.\nA larger choir is needed for this\ninter denominational, community\npageant. Any persons desiring to\njoin in the effort are requested\nto contact John Rodgers, Minister\nof Music at the Central Baptist\nChurch. The music is familiar, and\nthere are only three rehearsals.\nLocal 2 of the Printing Press\nmen in Detroit has presented the\nfirst pension checks to members\nwho had been employed in com\nmercial shops. The labor-man\nagement plan covers 6,000 em\nployees in 106 Detroit and Michi\ngan printing plants.\nSEC\nCEMENT COAT\nBeautiful and Decorative\nWaterproofing\nSee Your Dealer\nSec Manufacturing Company\nMANY HAPPY RETURNS\nW e Extend Hearty Rirthday Greetings To\nlabor Citizen\nAnd To Its Editor-Publisher, Charles F. Towle, and\nTo The Almost 100,000 Members of AFL-CIO in\nDade County, For Whom The Labor Citizen Serves\nas Official Organ, L T pon The 40th Anniversary of\nFlorida\u2019s Oldest Labor Newspaper. May You Have\nMany More Years of Service To Organized Labor\nand Labor-Management Relations and To The Greater\nMiami Community.\nFEDERAL\nTITLE\nAND\nINSURANCE\nCORPORATION\nESCROWS\nABSTRACTS\nTITLE INSURANCE\n1527 Washington Avenue\nMIAMI BEACH\n687 N. E. 124th Street\nNORTH MIAMI\nStrike In Peoria\nWon by Newsmen\nPEORIA, Hl.\u2014A 68-day strike\nby the Peoria Newspaper Guild\nagainst the Journal Star has been\nsettled with agreement on a con\ntract containing major gains for\nthe union.\nSettlement came after manage\nment agreed to a Guild proposal\ncalling for arbitration of the issue\nwhich caused the walkout\nwhether sick leave would be paid\nfrom the first day\u2019s illness, as has\nbeen the practice, or from the\neighth day.\nContract improvements included\npay boosts, increasing the top\nminimum from $llO a week to\n$113.50, a $4 a week general in\ncrease, a modified Guild shop, a\nnight differential, job security in\ncluding full grievance procedures,\nsix paid holidays and three weeks\nof vacation after five years.\nOUT OF LUCK\n\u201cWho was it that said that Sher\nman Adams will not be eligible to\nrun for President in 1960, because\nby that time he already will have\nserved two terms.\u201d Hannibal\n(Mo.) Labor Press.\nThe\nDade County\nFederation of Labor\nRecommends the following\nbroadcast to members of\nOrganized Labor:\nEdward P. Morgan\nAFL-CIO\nMonday thru Friday\n7:00-7:15 p.m.\nW K AT\nJohn W. Vandercook\nMonday thru Friday\nAFL-CIO\n10:00-10:05 p.m.\nWK AT","height":"27917","width":"18705"}}
